{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6d94b381-0fc2-4089-9143-ac4c030a1f0d","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n1. **User-level crashes:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level crashes:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for files matching your process name, e.g. `MyApp-2026-05-13-*.ips`.\n\n**Quick lookup:**\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head\n```\n\n**You can also use Console.app** → select \"Crash Reports\" in the sidebar.\n\n**For a core dump** (if you need one for `lldb`):\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen re-run your app. Core files go to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> **Tip:** If you need to symbolicate the `.ips` crash log against .NET runtime symbols, consider using the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill — just let me know!","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5228d37b-4cd1-4eec-9124-86260bd0c8ec","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a diagnostic question — let me answer from knowledge.","outputTokens":324,"requestId":"DA00:32F277:5267D4:5E1E05:6A03D862"},"id":"85755da9-80ee-4f5d-97e4-7d7836571213","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:48:27.044Z","parentId":"09d32fe4-6885-4973-97eb-9b86cb64bcfd"}
